ce:section.ce:para:
Since the discovery of carbon dots (CDs), a variety of synthesis routes have been explored. Most of the studies pursue facile, cost-effective, size-controllable, and large-scale technologies to synthesize CDs with enhanced functionality with diverse compositions and structures [70]. The fabrication of CDs can be broadly categorized into two approaches are based on cutting larger carbon materials “top-down” and fusing smaller precursor molecules “bottom-up” (Fig. 3
                        ). Even though both top-down and bottom-up approaches have been employed for CD synthesis, the environmentally and cost-effective bottom-up approach is most generally adopted, particularly for natural product CDs. In general, the bottom-up approach has a high yield and it convenient to introduce heteroatom doping into the synthesis process. Here, we will introduce some representative preparation methods for CDs and compare their advantages and disadvantages in Table 1
                        .
